             <a><a/><p><font color = "#FF6600">Living on Mars, scientists believe would be similar to living in the remote science outposts in the Antarctica – with all supplies needing to be shipped in and few escape routes in an emergency.  Since Mars is much farther away from the sun (141 million miles) than Earth (93 million miles), it is also much colder – the temperatures can reach as low as -284F in the winter at the poles, and as high as 86F in the summer at noon at the equator. The average temperature on Mars varies from a high of 70F on a warm summer day to -175 F on a cold winter night, making the type of shelter that can withstand such extremes critical. Because the temperatures fluctuate so wildly, astronauts will have to have suits that can keep them warm in the bitter cold as well as keeping them cool at the higher temperatures.  </font></p>
			 
