            <p><font color = "#FF6600">However, to terraform Mars to make it inhabitable for significant populations of humans, scientists would need to work toward warming the planet permanently.  Since the extreme temperatures are caused by Mars’ thin atmosphere which is only 1% of Earth’s, some suggestions to thicken the atmosphere have included importing the carbons that cause global warming on Earth to Mars until it is warm enough to sustain life – both plants and animals – that is common on Earth.  All suggestions to date, however would take many centuries, perhaps millions of years. </font></p>
			
			
            <p><font color = "#FF6600">Because Mar’s low temperature operates with the planet’s thin atmosphere, it makes water feasible in only two forms – gaseous vapor and solid ice. Any means of transporting liquid-water to the surface of Mars would instantaneously boil or freeze the water. Scientists have speculated that liquid-water which shaped the Mars gullies most likely boiled in an explosive manner after it erupted from beneath the surface.</font></p>
			
            <p><font color = "#FF6600">There is also ice on Mars, but it is not made of water as it is here on Earth, but rather of carbon dioxide instead.  We can see from radar pictures that the layered polar deposits grow during the winter and shrink during the summer.Like tree rings here on Earth, there are thick layers of ice separated by fine layers of ice and dust represent millions of years of climate change.</font>
			
